  "body": "**üßê Motivation**\r\nAdd documentation on using Upgrade Safe fork\r\n\r\n**üìù Details**\r\nCreate guide on when and how to use Upgrade Safe fork.\r\n\r\nInclude:\r\n* When to use chained and unchained initializers\r\n* What `_gap` is used for.\r\n\r\nWe could use something based on the following:\r\nUpgrade Safe contracts have two initializers: \"chained\" and \"unchained\". \r\n\r\n\"chain\" refers to the linearized chain of parent contracts, the main init contains a chain/sequence of calls to the unchained initializers of the parent contracts.  If we called the chained versions we would be making multiple calls to the \"grandparent\" initializer.\r\n\r\n`__gap` is an empty storage gap put in each Upgrade Safe contract. This allows in future versions new storage variables to be added to a contract.\r\nIt isn't safe to simply add a storage variable because it \"shifts down\" all of the storage variables down the inheritance chain. This makes the storage layouts incompatible, (see: https://docs.openzeppelin.com/upgrades-plugins/1.x/writing-upgradeable#modifying-your-contracts).  The number is calculated so that the size of the storage used by a contract always adds up to the same number (e.g. 100).",
